{
  "texts": [
    "The former aims to find hallucinated tokens while the latter is to identify the sentences with hallucinations.",
    "Various methods have been developed for identifying hallucinations and most of them leverage the pre-trained LLMs fine tuned on task-specific data (Liu et al., 2021; Dziri et al., 2021; Cao et al., 2021; Zha et al., 2023).",
    "More recently, LLM with promptbased methods are also widely used (Manakul et al., 2023; Lei et al., 2023).",
    "Though the prompt-based methods require little to no tuning and have competitive performance, they tend to have higher cost and higher latency.",
    "In our study, we've harnessed the strengths of both methods by employing LLM-based detection for labeling data and creating an ensemble of tailored traditional models such as NER, NLI, and span-based sequence labeling."
  ]
}